Data clean

Data import - Charlotte housing data

rr # Import full Charlotte housing data load(file = _clt.Rdata) # Import matched Charlotte housing data load(file = _clt.Rdata)

Clean and format data on Charlotte house prices - full data

rr # Filter on conditions that arent realistic for houses in full Charlotte dataframe full_clt = full_clt_df %>% rename(eoccomposite = EOC Composite , eocdifference = EOC Difference , half_baths = half baths) %>% mutate( daily = ymd(sold) , new = ifelse(new_construct == , 1 , 0) , age = 2010 - year_built , agesq = age^2 , lrsp = log(rsp) , lrlp = log(rlp) ) %>% filter( !(baths > 6) ) %>% filter( !(acres > 10) ) %>% filter( !(age < 0) ) %>% filter( !(age > 200) ) %>% filter( !(total_hla == 0) ) %>% filter( !(baths == 0 & half_baths == 0) ) %>% filter( !(baths == 0) ) %>% filter( !(beds < 1) ) %>% filter( !(rsp < 1000) ) %>% filter( !(treat == 1 & eocdifference < 0) ) %>% filter( !(treat == 2 & eocdifference > 0) )

rr # Aggregate lrsp data to lrsp averages for each day during sample timeframe (positive treatment and control groups) monthly_lrsp_pos = full_clt %>% filter( treat %in% c(0,1) ) %>% mutate( monthly = month(daily) , yearly = year(daily) , yearmon = ymd(paste0(yearly,-,monthly,-01)) ) %>% group_by(yearmon , treat) %>% summarize( lrsp = mean(lrsp) , n = n() ) # Aggregate lrsp data to lrsp averages for each day during sample timeframe (negative treatment and control groups) monthly_lrsp_neg = full_clt %>% filter( treat %in% c(0,2) ) %>% mutate( monthly = month(daily) , yearly = year(daily) , yearmon = ymd(paste0(yearly,-,monthly,-01)) ) %>% group_by(yearmon , treat) %>% summarize( lrsp = mean(lrsp) )

Notes:

  • Data issues from MLS in late 1999 to early 2001 obfuscate empirical trend lines and house prices (average monthly house prices during this period calculated from small numbers of house sales, sometimes 1, 2, 3. Some months have no house sales). Had this data not been lost, would have seen sharper patterns and likely closer trend lines without such a disparate drop down. Story here is in the slopes, not the immediate effects! (Lottery offset these)

  • Trends essentially parallel in positive/control pre-busing period; clear change in trends afterward, with positive control group of neighborhood-houses continuing upward trajectory, while control switch tack. Also, large drop-down relative to positively treated neighborhoods indicates bigger negative effect at first and then substantial on-going effects from change in school assignment policy. People bidding up house prices in these areas relative to control houses (which are fall in house price post-busing).

  • Negative trends tell another side of the story: no immediate effects for negatiely treated houses relative to controls; negative slope didnt change much either. Control slope, as before, is (would be less) slightly positive until busing decision, then gradually negative afterward. Negative prices bid down slightly faster in post-busing era.

Regression analyses

Linear DiD models

Linear models encapsulate both dummy-treatment and EOC-difference treatment.

Set up variables for treatment and control groups (positively and negatively treated). This requires dummies for treated (positively and negatively) and date sold (pre- and post-April 12, 2002)

rr # Treatments are categorical here (0,1 and interactions) and for date sold before/after rezoning treated_df = full_clt %>% mutate( year_fe = factor(year(daily)) ) %>% # First are neighborhood treatments mutate( rezone = ifelse(treat == 1 | treat == 2 , 1 , 0) ) %>% # Next are date treatments mutate( post2002 = ifelse(sold < 002-04-15, 0 , 1) ) %>% # Interaction of two is treatment, positive treatment, and negative treatment mutate( treat = rezonepost2002 ) # Positively treated dataframe treated_pos_df = full_clt %>% filter( treat %in% c(0,1) ) %>% mutate( year_fe = factor(year(daily)) ) %>% # First are neighborhood treatments mutate( rezonepos = ifelse(treat == 1 , 1 , 0) ) %>% # Next are date treatments mutate( post2002 = ifelse(sold < 002-04-15, 0 , 1) ) %>% # Interaction of two is treatment, positive treatment, and negative treatment mutate( treatpos = rezonepospost2002 , eocptreat = eocdifferencetreatpos) # Positively treated dataframe treated_neg_df = full_clt %>% filter( treat %in% c(0,2) ) %>% mutate( year_fe = factor(year(daily)) ) %>% # First are neighborhood treatments mutate( rezoneneg = ifelse(treat == 2 , 1 , 0) ) %>% # Next are date treatments mutate( post2002 = ifelse(sold < 002-04-15, 0 , 1) ) %>% # Interaction of two is treatment, positive treatment, and negative treatment mutate( treatneg = rezonenegpost2002 , eocntreat = eocdifference*treatneg)

Apply same models to treatment quantiles (break treatment into bottom 25%, middle 50%, and top 25% of EOC difference totals)

Positive model results: EOC quantiles


# Positively treated houses quantiles of EOC-difference scores
quant_pos_df = treated_pos_df %>%
  mutate( eocp25 = ifelse(eocdifference != 0 & eocdifference <= 6.93 , 1 , 0) ,
          eocp50 = ifelse(6.93 < eocdifference & eocdifference < 32.3 , 1 , 0) ,
          eocp75 = ifelse(32.3 <= eocdifference , 1 , 0) )

# Bottom 25% of EOC differences
quant_pos_25 = quant_pos_df %>%
  filter( eocp25 == 1 | eocdifference == 0 )

# Middle 50% of EOC differences
quant_pos_50 = quant_pos_df %>%
  filter( eocp50 == 1 | eocdifference == 0 )

# Upper 25% of EOC differences
quant_pos_75 = quant_pos_df %>%
  filter( eocp75 == 1 | eocdifference == 0 )

# Linear model incorporating all three treatment effects

# Bottom 25%

                clusters = quant_pos_25$subdiv) )
